# Next.js Guidelines

## App Router

- Use the App Router for all new routes
- Organize routes logically in the app directory
- Use layout components for shared UI elements
- Implement error boundaries with error.tsx files
- Use loading.tsx for loading states

## Server Components vs. Client Components

- Use Server Components by default
- Add "use client" directive only when necessary:
  - When using hooks (useState, useEffect, etc.)
  - When using browser-only APIs
  - When attaching event handlers
- Keep client components as small as possible
- Pass data from server components to client components

## Data Fetching

- Use server components for data fetching when possible
- Implement proper caching strategies:
  - Use `cache: 'force-cache'` for static data
  - Use `next: { revalidate: seconds }` for ISR
  - Use `cache: 'no-store'` for dynamic data
- Handle loading and error states appropriately
- Use React Suspense for streaming

## Routing

- Use dynamic routes for variable paths
- Implement proper route groups with parentheses
- Use parallel routes for complex layouts
- Implement intercepting routes when needed
- Use route handlers for API endpoints

## Metadata

- Implement proper metadata for SEO
- Use dynamic metadata generation
- Include appropriate Open Graph tags
- Implement proper canonical URLs

## Image Optimization

- Use Next.js Image component for all images
- Specify appropriate sizes and quality
- Use responsive images with appropriate breakpoints
- Implement proper loading strategies (eager/lazy)

## Performance

- Implement proper code splitting
- Use dynamic imports for large components
- Optimize Third-Party Scripts
- Implement proper font loading strategies
- Use Next.js Analytics to monitor performance

## Deployment

- Use Vercel for deployment
- Set up proper environment variables
- Implement proper preview deployments
- Use Vercel Analytics for monitoring